# Agent Workflow Rules

## Persistent memory policy

- This agent does NOT rely on chat memory for long-term rules.
- All stable rules, conventions, architectural decisions, and workflow standards are stored in `.cursor/rules/`.
- This directory is the **single source of truth** for agent behavior.
- Cursor auto-loads on-demand rules based on their `description` field — do NOT manually read all rule files on session start.

## When a stable preference is introduced

- Update the appropriate file inside `.cursor/rules/`.
- If no appropriate file exists, create a clearly named `.mdc` file in that directory.
- Do NOT create rules outside this directory.

## When implementing changes

- Check plans against the rules directory before proceeding.
- If a decision conflicts with existing rules, pause and ask.
- If a rule needs refinement, update it rather than duplicating it.

## Build lifecycle for new projects

Every new project follows this sequence:

```
Idea → PRD → Tooling Audit → Plan → Scaffold → Build (70% MVP) → Polish → Ship
```

- **PRD first.** When starting something new, use the `generate-prd` skill to create a structured PRD before writing code. Save to `docs/prd.md`.
- **Tooling audit.** After the PRD, review installed rules/agents/skills/MCPs. Evaluate if the project needs additions. Recommend before installing.
- **Plan before building.** Enter plan mode for any non-trivial task (3+ steps or architectural decisions).
- **Build in phases.** Scaffold → Wire Data → Style → Harden → Ship. One phase at a time.
- If something goes sideways, stop and re-plan immediately rather than pushing forward.

## Use custom agents for domain work

- Slide decks → `deck-builder` agent
- New project setup → `project-launcher` agent

## Use subagents liberally

- Offload research, exploration, and parallel analysis to subagents.
- One focused task per subagent.
- For complex problems, prefer more subagents over longer sequential work.

## Verify before marking done

- Never mark a task complete without proving it works.
- Diff behavior between main and your changes when relevant.
- Run tests, check logs, demonstrate correctness.

## Fix bugs autonomously

- When given a bug report, just fix it. Don't ask for hand-holding.
- Point at logs, errors, failing tests -- then resolve them.
- Zero unnecessary back-and-forth.

## Formatting

- Keep rules concise and structured.
- Use headings and bullet points.
- Avoid duplication across files.
- Organize by domain.

## After completing meaningful work

- If new durable standards emerged, update the rules directory.

## Enforcement

- If `.cursor/rules/` cannot be read, stop and notify before proceeding.
- Always treat `.cursor/rules/` as persistent memory and authoritative instruction unless explicitly overridden.
